MiniWorld is designer & traveler Danny Sanchez's vision to create the biggest and best collection of 3D printable World Landmarks.

Designed in SolidWorks/Fusion 360 purposefully for 3D printing, models are optimized for household FDM printing. Results in more professional equipment are simply stunning.
.
.
The Idea

A visually-impaired friend asked Danny if 3D printing could be used to help her and others "see" the world - have you ever thought about that? - blind people can't see a world atlas or postcards, and if they visit a landmark, all they touch is usually a stone wall. With miniature models, they can understand shapes and sizes of the most famous buildings and travel with their hands. MiniWorld now has a catalog of more than 70 models from 30 countries for everybody to enjoy - and growing!
.
.
Contributors

Aside from Danny, other designers have joined MiniWorld's mission and kindly contribute with their work. Check out their personal profiles!

I started my career as a stand-up comic but success and recognition remains elusive, thus two years ago (December 2014), broken and sad faced, walking down a nameless street, disgusted and annoyed by the ever increasing number of hipsters prancing around like morris dancers whoo de doo... I ventured into the nearest nerdiest shop for refuge, a shop with the glaring fluorescent name of Maplin.

In it, friendly staffers dressed alike in baby blue polo tees, unabashedly friendly, greeted with curious smile. It was after all nearing Christmas. All manner of flashing leds and R/C toys adore its aisles, LOLz there's a voice changing kids-sized megaphone! That's one darn good gift for my nephew!

Then there it was whizzing frenetically, haltingly catching its next step (or what can only be described as in words like Tron racing racers), was this magically thingamajig. It create three dimensional object! Albeit disappointingly slow, but mesmerizing nevertheless, hypnotic even...

Dear god! I am become death! Destroy it will to me and my pockets! It is Soooooo expensive! AND you have to assemble it yourself?! WTF! Made in Italy? Like Farrari maybe...

Days past and my career really faltered, like gutter-level 11, worst than bathroom scum, the pinkish kind that needs scrubbing. I really needed something to kick start that resilient "growth mindset" radio four was chattering about... Purse string loosen, what the heck! I've brought one!

Delivery was an extremely heavy rectangular box, bags after bags of stuff, bits and bobs, screws for every nook and crannies. The long and short of it, took me quite a while to assemble THE MACHINE, not particularly enjoyable, but it work 100% in the end...

And on the anniversary of its conception, having learnt the tools, the Velleman K8200 gave birth to a new daughter machine, seven month later, a granddaughter machine was born.

So come the day when you can realised your idea and they are no longer constrained by the tools you have, you can make dreams come true! XOXO

Technology whether it is television, the Internet, mobile devices, or a combination of all three, has the power to influence change. My perspective on social causes has been molded by technology throughout my life, and in my work I use the power of these technologies to promote education and awareness.

The television, and subsequently the computer, has continually influenced my education. From early on, I have been inclined to ask for knowledge from the screen rather than the teacher. Now as an educator, knowing this to be true in those who seek understanding from me, I try to create new ways of pursuing learning and understanding through the use of technology and documentary.

My present work consists of experimenting with â€œoff the shelfâ€ technology to create visual learning experiences. Its objective is to bring attention to social causes while using media technology to further enhance and justify social goals.
